---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .circuit-card {
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 18px 20px;
      background: var(--card);
      margin-bottom: 12px;
    }
    .circuit-card .ct-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .circuit-card .ct-path {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11.5px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
    .circuit-card .ct-desc { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 12px; }
    .io-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 10px; }
    .io-block {
      border: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
      border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
      padding: 10px 12px;
      background: var(--muted);
    }
    .io-block .io-label {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 10px;
      color: var(--text-faint);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.1em;
      margin-bottom: 6px;
    }
    .io-block .io-list {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11.5px;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      line-height: 1.6;
    }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="22 · ZK Privacy Stack — Sardis Canvas" currentId="zk-privacy">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 22 · Extended</span>
        <h1>ZK Privacy Stack</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Prove a payment satisfied its policy, mandate, funding, and identity requirements —
          without revealing the amounts, the limits, the merchant, or the agent. Sardis ships two
          Noir circuit packages (<code>sardis-zk-policy</code>, <code>sardis-zkp</code>), a deterministic
          Python simulator for CI, and three adjacent runtime layers — <code>sardis-ucp</code>,
          <code>sardis-guardrails</code>, and the <code>PreExecutionPipeline</code> — that decide when
          a clear-text decision needs to turn into a proof.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          Enterprises can't publish raw spending logs to auditors — the logs are the product.
          ZK lets the same row say "this payment was within all 11 policy rules" without showing
          per-transaction amounts, merchant identities, or the limits that define the rules.
          Sardis uses <strong>Noir + Barretenberg</strong> (Aztec) for the circuits, because the
          toolchain is audited, the proving backend is fast enough for per-transaction use, and
          verification is cheap enough to run on-chain via <code>SardisLedgerAnchor</code>.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Status -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Status</div>
          <h2>What ships vs. what's experimental.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            The ZK stack is real code — two Noir projects, working circuits, a Python simulator used in CI.
            It is not on the default hot path. Today it runs as an <em>alternative</em> policy check for
            tenants that explicitly opt in; the clear-text <code>PreExecutionPipeline</code> remains the
            production default.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Component</th><th>Maturity</th><th>Deployed</th><th>Gate</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>sardis-zk-policy</code> (Noir circuit + simulator)</td><td>Feature-complete for 5 / 11 policy checks</td><td>No (opt-in)</td><td>Requires <code>nargo</code> installed in the runtime image.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis-zkp</code> (mandate / identity / funding circuits)</td><td>Circuits compile, dev-mode mock proofs only</td><td>No</td><td><code>production=True</code> on <code>ZKProver</code> — refuses to mock-verify otherwise.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis-ucp</code> (Universal Commerce Protocol)</td><td>Shipped</td><td>Yes</td><td>Public surface; feeds checkout + AP2 adapters.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>sardis-guardrails</code> (circuit breaker, kill switch, limiter, ML fraud)</td><td>Shipped</td><td>Yes</td><td>Always on. Not ZK — classical runtime safety layer.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Why Noir -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Backend Choice</div>
          <h2>Why Noir (Aztec) — and not Circom / Halo2 / RISC0.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Rust-like syntax, small surface</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Circuit authors are Python and Rust engineers, not cryptographers. Noir reads like Rust —
              <code>assert</code>, <code>for</code>, <code>if</code>, <code>u64</code> — which keeps the
              policy circuit reviewable alongside the clear-text Python implementation in
              <code>policy_circuit_sim.py</code>.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">ACIR → ACVM → Barretenberg</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Noir compiles to <strong>ACIR</strong> (intermediate representation), executed by the
              <strong>ACVM</strong> witness solver, and proven by <strong>Barretenberg</strong> (UltraPlonk
              + Honk). That layering means we can swap proving backends later without rewriting circuits.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Audited toolchain</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Aztec audits its compiler and prover. The alternative — hand-rolled Circom — requires writing
              templates + solvers + verifiers that all need independent review. For a fintech, using an
              audited toolchain is cheaper than auditing custom R1CS.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Cheap on-chain verification</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Barretenberg emits Solidity verifier contracts. One ZK policy proof verifies in ~300K gas on
              Base L2 — low enough to anchor alongside the Merkle batch from <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code>
              without blowing the per-batch cost model.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- sardis-zk-policy -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Package · sardis-zk-policy</div>
          <h2>Policy circuit — 5 of 11 checks in zero knowledge.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            A single Noir binary at <code>packages/sardis-zk-policy/src/main.nr</code>. Private inputs
            carry the transaction + policy parameters; a single public input pair
            (<code>evidence_hash_high</code>, <code>evidence_hash_low</code>) links the proof to the
            off-chain policy decision log.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="circuit-card">
          <div class="ct-title">main.nr — policy compliance proof</div>
          <div class="ct-path">packages/sardis-zk-policy/src/main.nr · Nargo.toml · Prover.toml · Verifier.toml</div>
          <div class="ct-desc">
            Proves all five checks in one circuit: per-tx cap, daily cap, MCC block-list membership,
            time-window (including wrap-around), and per-merchant cap. Asserts <code>evidence_hash</code>
            is non-zero so the off-chain row is addressable.
          </div>
          <div class="io-grid">
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Private inputs (witness)</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                amount: u64<br/>
                daily_total: u64<br/>
                merchant_total: u64<br/>
                mcc_hash: u64<br/>
                hour: u8<br/>
                max_per_transaction: u64<br/>
                daily_limit: u64<br/>
                per_merchant_limit: u64<br/>
                window_start: u8<br/>
                window_end: u8<br/>
                blocked_mcc_hashes: [u64; 8]
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Public inputs</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                evidence_hash_high: pub u128<br/>
                evidence_hash_low: pub u128
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="circuit-card">
          <div class="ct-title">policy_circuit_sim.py — bit-exact Python mirror</div>
          <div class="ct-path">packages/sardis-zk-policy/python/policy_circuit_sim.py · types.py</div>
          <div class="ct-desc">
            A Python function that runs the same five checks in the same order, producing a
            <code>CircuitResult(passed, failed_check)</code>. Used in CI for fast regression tests; the
            companion suite <code>tests/test_noir_equivalence.py</code> is designed to pin Noir output
            to the Python output once <code>nargo prove</code> is wired into CI.
          </div>
          <div class="io-grid">
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">API</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                simulate_circuit(private, public)<br/>
                prepare_circuit_inputs(...)<br/>
                mcc_to_hash(mcc_code)<br/>
                evidence_hash_to_pair(hex)
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Guarantees</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                Same assert order as main.nr<br/>
                Same wrap-around time logic<br/>
                Same MCC zero-slot handling<br/>
                Deterministic, no I/O
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- sardis-zkp -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Package · sardis-zkp</div>
          <h2>Reusable circuit library — mandate, identity, funding.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            Three Noir circuits under <code>packages/sardis-zkp/circuits/</code>, orchestrated by a Python
            <code>ZKProver</code> in <code>src/lib.py</code>. Each circuit targets one question; together
            they cover the questions Sardis actually needs to answer in ZK at the mandate layer.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="circuit-card">
          <div class="ct-title">mandate_compliance.nr — payment within mandate bounds</div>
          <div class="ct-path">packages/sardis-zkp/circuits/mandate_compliance.nr</div>
          <div class="ct-desc">
            Proves <code>amount ≤ per_tx_limit</code> AND <code>daily_spent + amount ≤ daily_limit</code>,
            and that the private inputs hash to the public <code>mandate_commitment</code> and
            <code>payment_commitment</code> (both Poseidon on BN254). Merchant inclusion via 8-deep
            Merkle proof; replay protection via <code>mandate_nonce</code>.
          </div>
          <div class="io-grid">
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Public</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                mandate_commitment: Field<br/>
                payment_commitment: Field
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Private</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                amount, per_tx_limit,<br/>
                daily_limit, daily_spent,<br/>
                merchant_id_hash,<br/>
                allowed_merchant_root,<br/>
                merchant_proof[8],<br/>
                mandate_nonce
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="circuit-card">
          <div class="ct-title">identity_proof.nr — KYA level without agent identity</div>
          <div class="ct-path">packages/sardis-zkp/circuits/identity_proof.nr</div>
          <div class="ct-desc">
            Proves the agent holds an attestation whose <code>kya_level ≥ required_kya_level</code>,
            unexpired, and not future-dated. Public side sees only the commitment + the threshold;
            the agent's id hash and the issuer remain private.
          </div>
          <div class="io-grid">
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Public</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                identity_commitment: Field<br/>
                required_kya_level: Field
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Private</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                agent_id_hash, kya_level,<br/>
                attestation_timestamp,<br/>
                attestation_expiry,<br/>
                current_timestamp,<br/>
                issuer_id_hash,<br/>
                attestation_nonce
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="circuit-card">
          <div class="ct-title">funding_sufficiency.nr — cells cover amount</div>
          <div class="ct-path">packages/sardis-zkp/circuits/funding_sufficiency.nr</div>
          <div class="ct-desc">
            Proves <code>sum(cell_values[0..16]) ≥ payment_amount</code> without revealing any individual
            cell value. Each cell is bounded to &lt; 2<sup>53</sup> to prevent field-overflow attacks.
            Commitments are Poseidon batches so the off-chain funding-cell set can be reconciled.
          </div>
          <div class="io-grid">
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Public</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                payment_amount: Field<br/>
                cells_commitment: Field
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="io-block">
              <div class="io-label">Private</div>
              <div class="io-list">
                cell_values[16], cell_ids[16],<br/>
                cell_count, currency_hash,<br/>
                nonce
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Privacy tiers -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Privacy Tiers</div>
          <h2>Transparent, hybrid, full ZK.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            Defined in <code>sardis_zkp.PrivacyTier</code>. Tenants select a tier per payment object
            (mandate, payment, wallet) — the orchestrator routes to the corresponding verifier path.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Tier</th><th>What's visible</th><th>What's hidden</th><th>When to use</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>TRANSPARENT</code></td><td>All fields (amount, merchant, limits, counterparty)</td><td>Nothing</td><td>Default. Consumer agents, developer sandboxes, public tokens.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>HYBRID</code></td><td>Merchant, chain, timestamp, decision outcome</td><td>Amount, limits</td><td>B2B payments where merchant identity is non-sensitive but commercial terms are.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>FULL_ZK</code></td><td>Proof only — commitments + verification result</td><td>Amount, merchant, limits, agent identity, funding cells</td><td>Enterprise treasury flows, regulated payouts, custodial agent fleets.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Which policies go ZK -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Coverage Matrix</div>
          <h2>Which policy checks translate to ZK — and which don't.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            The <code>SpendingPolicy</code> engine has ~11 check types. Five are implemented in
            <code>main.nr</code> today. The rest either need oracle data, a running graph, or third-party
            attestations that can't be proven in-circuit without leaking the external state.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Policy check</th><th>ZK today</th><th>ZK feasible</th><th>Why / why not</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Per-transaction cap</td><td>Yes</td><td>—</td><td>Pure numeric comparison.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Daily aggregate cap</td><td>Yes</td><td>—</td><td>Running total carried as private input.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Per-merchant cap</td><td>Yes</td><td>—</td><td>Keyed by <code>merchant_id_hash</code>; same shape as daily.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>MCC block-list</td><td>Yes (8 slots)</td><td>—</td><td>Set-membership via linear scan; extend to Merkle for larger lists.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Time window (with wrap)</td><td>Yes</td><td>—</td><td>Hour as u8; handled in both linear and wrap case.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Allowed-merchant Merkle root</td><td>Partial (in <code>sardis-zkp</code> mandate)</td><td>Yes</td><td>Need to wire merchant registry → Merkle root into prover input.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>KYC/AML status</td><td>No</td><td>Yes, via attested credential</td><td>Requires a KYC-provider-signed attestation usable inside circuit.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Sanctions / OFAC screen</td><td>No</td><td>Partial</td><td>Elliptic API is external; proof would cover attestation, not live screen.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Anomaly score threshold</td><td>No</td><td>Partial</td><td>Score is an ML output; circuit could assert a signed score, not compute it.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Rate limit (token bucket)</td><td>No</td><td>Yes, with state commitment</td><td>Needs a commitment to bucket state; opens replay questions.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Kill switch / emergency stop</td><td>No</td><td>No</td><td>Kill switch is operator intent, not a math fact. Stays clear-text.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Prover flow Mermaid -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Flow</div>
          <h2>Prover → verifier, end to end.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            A ZK-tier payment takes the same orchestrator spine as a transparent one — it just forks at
            the policy check into a proof-generation path instead of a direct assert.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
sequenceDiagram
    participant A as Agent
    participant O as PaymentOrchestrator
    participant P as PreExecutionPipeline
    participant ZP as ZKProver (sardis-zkp)
    participant N as Noir / nargo
    participant L as Ledger + Anchor
    participant V as On-chain Verifier

    A->>O: execute(intent, privacy_tier=FULL_ZK)
    O->>P: run classical gates (rate limit, kill switch)
    P->>ZP: prove_mandate_compliance(amount, limits)
    ZP->>N: write Prover.toml + nargo prove
    N-->>ZP: proof bytes + public inputs
    ZP->>P: ZKProof(commitments, bytes)
    P->>P: hash evidence row → evidence_hash
    P->>ZP: prove_policy(evidence_hash, witness)
    ZP-->>P: policy proof bytes
    P-->>O: approved (ZK)
    O->>L: append row + attach proofs
    L->>V: submit Merkle root + ZK proof batch
    V-->>L: on-chain receipt
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Example -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Worked Example</div>
          <h2>"Prove spending was under $500 today — without per-tx amounts."</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Concrete path through <code>sardis-zk-policy</code> for a single transaction. All amounts
            scaled to integer minor-units (1 USDC = 1,000,000).
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Prover side (private)</div>
            <dl class="defs">
              <dt>amount</dt><dd>47_500000  (47.50 USDC)</dd>
              <dt>daily_total</dt><dd>392_000000  (already spent today)</dd>
              <dt>max_per_transaction</dt><dd>250_000000</dd>
              <dt>daily_limit</dt><dd>500_000000</dd>
              <dt>hour / window</dt><dd>14 / [09, 18]</dd>
              <dt>mcc_hash</dt><dd><code>sha256("5812")[:8]</code></dd>
              <dt>blocked_mcc_hashes</dt><dd>[gambling, crypto_mx, ...]</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Public (what verifiers see)</div>
            <dl class="defs">
              <dt>evidence_hash</dt><dd><code>sha256(decision_row)</code></dd>
              <dt>→ high / low</dt><dd>two u128 values</dd>
              <dt>Verifier checks</dt><dd>Barretenberg verifier accepts the proof against the compiled circuit and the public inputs.</dd>
              <dt>Auditor sees</dt><dd>"Policy row <code>pol_0x…</code> passed all 5 in-circuit checks." No amounts. No merchant. No limits.</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Adjacent: UCP -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Adjacent · sardis-ucp</div>
          <h2>Universal Commerce Protocol — the object model ZK wraps.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            UCP is not ZK, but it defines the commerce primitives (<code>UCPCartMandate</code>,
            <code>UCPPaymentMandate</code>, <code>UCPOrder</code>, <code>UCPCheckoutCapability</code>) that
            ZK proofs reference as commitment inputs. When <code>mandate_compliance.nr</code> takes a
            <code>payment_commitment</code>, the preimage is a UCP mandate object.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>UCP primitive</th><th>File</th><th>ZK touch point</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>UCPPaymentMandate</code> / <code>UCPCartMandate</code></td><td><code>packages/sardis-ucp/src/sardis_ucp/models/mandates.py</code></td><td>Commitment preimage for <code>mandate_compliance</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>UCPCheckoutCapability</code></td><td><code>packages/sardis-ucp/src/sardis_ucp/capabilities/checkout.py</code></td><td>Session lifecycle — where privacy tier is chosen.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>UCPOrder</code> / <code>UCPFulfillment</code></td><td><code>packages/sardis-ucp/src/sardis_ucp/models/orders.py</code></td><td>Post-settlement state; fulfillment events anchor next to ZK receipts.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>ap2.py</code> adapter</td><td><code>packages/sardis-ucp/src/sardis_ucp/adapters/ap2.py</code></td><td>Translates AP2 Intent → Cart → Payment into UCP, so AP2 flows can opt into ZK.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Transports (REST, MCP)</td><td><code>packages/sardis-ucp/src/sardis_ucp/transports/</code></td><td>Declare privacy tier on the wire.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Adjacent: Guardrails -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Adjacent · sardis-guardrails</div>
          <h2>Classical runtime safety — always in front of the proof.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            Guardrails are not ZK; they run first. A proof that a payment satisfied a policy is worthless
            if the agent is on the kill list or the circuit breaker is tripped. Guardrails answer
            "should we even be computing a proof right now?"
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Module</th><th>Role</th><th>When it fires</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>circuit_breaker.py</code></td><td>Automatic failure isolation per agent</td><td>N consecutive failures → reject without prover work.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>kill_switch.py</code></td><td>Global / per-org / per-agent hard stop</td><td>Operator or <code>FRAUD</code>/<code>ANOMALY</code> auto-trip.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>rate_limiter.py</code></td><td>Token-bucket + sliding window</td><td>Too many tx or too much amount per minute/hour.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>input_validator.py</code></td><td>Address / amount / chain / token validation</td><td>Before any downstream work, including proving.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>behavioral_monitor.py</code> + <code>anomaly_engine.py</code> + <code>ml_fraud.py</code></td><td>Statistical / ML anomaly scoring</td><td>Generates signed score that a ZK circuit can consume.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>graph_fraud.py</code></td><td>Graph-level counterparty analysis</td><td>Runs over counterparty network; feeds FIDES trust graph.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>agent_threat_detector.py</code> · <code>fingerprint.py</code> · <code>ft3_taxonomy.py</code></td><td>Agent-level threat classification</td><td>Feeds KYA attestations used by <code>identity_proof.nr</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>zen_engine.py</code></td><td>Rules DSL executor</td><td>Declarative merchant / policy rules applied pre-orchestrator.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Integration -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Integration</div>
          <h2>Where ZK hooks into the spine.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:740px;">
            The <code>PreExecutionPipeline</code> runs all transactions through the same ordered gate
            (see canvas 01 · Architecture). The ZK path is a fork <em>inside</em> the policy gate, not a
            parallel pipeline — everything else (mandate check, AP2 verify, rate limit, kill switch) is
            shared with the transparent path.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">What the orchestrator does differently</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              On <code>privacy_tier=FULL_ZK</code>, the policy check returns a <code>ZKProof</code> instead
              of a boolean. The orchestrator attaches the proof to the ledger row, and the Merkle batch
              submission includes proof bytes for on-chain verification.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">What stays the same</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Kill switch, rate limit, input validation, MPC signing path, CCTP settlement, reconciliation
              queue. ZK changes what is <em>seen</em>; it doesn't change what is <em>done</em>.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Dev vs. prod mode</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>ZKProver(production=False)</code> emits JSON placeholder proof bytes and <em>refuses</em>
              to verify. <code>production=True</code> shells out to <code>nargo prove</code> /
              <code>nargo verify</code> in the circuit directory. Mock verify was removed on purpose to stop
              anyone from mistaking dev mode for security.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">On-chain anchor</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Verifier contracts generated by Barretenberg are deployed alongside
              <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code> (canvas 06). A batch root + proof tuple posted there is
              independently verifiable by any third party without reading Sardis logs.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

